It's one of the many magnificent gates in the courtyard and named after the Hindu god Ganesh and is the entry into what was originally the private palaces of the Maharajas of Amer.</span></div></div><div class="lszDU" style="line-height: 22px;"><button class="UikNM _G B- _S _T c G_ P0 wSSLS wnNQG" type="button"><span class="biGQs _P XWJSj Wb">Read more</span><div class="CECjK"><svg viewBox="0 0 25 24" width="20px" height="20px" class="d Vb UmNoP"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M5.188 7.521l6.836 6.837 6.837-6.837 1.06 1.06-7.366 7.368a.75.75 0 01-1.061 0L4.127 8.582l1.06-1.06z"></path></svg></div></button></div></div><div></div><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB xUqsL mowmC KxBGd"><a target="_blank" tabindex="0" href="/Attraction_Review-g304555-d2648786-Reviews-Ganesh_Pol_Gateway-Jaipur_Jaipur_District_Rajasthan.html#REVIEWS" class="BMQDV _F G- wSSLS SwZTJ FGwzt suezE">Review of: Ganesh Pol Gateway</a></div><div class="TreSq"><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB ncFvv osNWb">Written 9 July 2020</div><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB mowmC osNWb">This review is the subjective opinion of a Tripadvisor member and not of Tripadvisor LLC. 10A10 10 0 012 12 10 10 0 0112 2z" transform="translate(104 0)"></path></svg></div><div class="biGQs _P fiohW qWPrE ncFvv fOtGX"><a target="_blank" tabindex="0" href="/ShowUserReviews-g304555-d2443557-r869453854-Galtaji_Temple-Jaipur_Jaipur_District_Rajasthan.html" class="BMQDV _F G- wSSLS SwZTJ FGwzt ukgoS"><span class="yCeTE">A mixed bag of memories</span></a></div><div class="_T FKffI bmUTE"><div class="fIrGe _T bgMZj" style="-webkit-line-clamp: 7; line-break: normal; cursor: pointer;"><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB KxBGd"><span class="yCeTE">GALTAJI is an ancient Hindu pilgrimage about six miles from Jaipur.<br>It consists of several temples built into a narrow cleft in the ring of hills surrounding the city.<br>The site is famous for its natural springs which collect in tanks. The holiest of these is Galta Kund which never goes dry.<br>It is considered auspicious to bathe in the waters of Galtaji and thousands come to do so every year. Therein lies a problem.<br>Firstly when you put people and their food together in a natural setting it attracts the local monkeys and they do things in the waters that you don't want to know about.<br>For that matter, the impact on the purity of the waters from scores and scores of people using it to bathe every day is also something you probably don't want to dwell on.<br>Add to that wandering cattle and their droppings, great heaps of rubbish lying about in the undergrowth, monkeys being fed plastic packets of milk with the stench later from that and you rightly get the impression that religious purity has become, to say the least, a little tarnished.<br>I should stress at this point that those visiting this cleft of temples should expect to be tested physically since I estimated the steep climb to the Sun Temple at the top and back down at close to two miles over frequently uneven and stony ground. Take care.<br>My way began up past one temple and up several sections of stone steps with a fence of razor wire on my left. Monkeys treated that barrier with contempt.<br>The human bathing area -- one for men and one for women -- was packed at one tank with people stripping off and plunging in while another tank I passed had several dozen monkeys individually and collectively swimming in its waters.<br>The path-passage took a sharp left and climbed past what seemed to be a popular monkey feeding point before the rough path climbed steeply up into the hills.<br>When I arrived at the Sun Temple it offered majestic views over Jaipur and a chance to get my breath back. It was a hot day and I needed the bottled water I had brought with me. Make sure you bring some too.<br>On the way down my guide pointed out a wonderful archaeological site of early 1700s astronomical instruments choked in trees and undergrowth near a huge pile of cow dung.<br>Apparently a much larger similar astronomical observatory site, Jantar Mantar, down in Jaipur got all the restoration money despite the fact that this overgrown site near the Sun Temple is actually older and, therefore, historically more important.<br>I am highlighting the situation in this and other related reviews in the hope Indian authorities spare a little money to restore this site too. It certainly deserves it because even neglect couldn't hide the lovely curved marble instruments, structures and scientific markings.<br>Coming on down we passed a holy man sat cross-legged on the pavement watching the world go by. I wonder what he thought of the changes to this religious site?<br>Back down towards the entrance we eased our way past the bathing bedlam, discarded drifts of monkey food and a few less savoury deposits to eventually drive away with very mixed memories.<br>The site itself should have been lovely with its tanks of water, historic temples, gorge-like setting and wonderful views, but mankind's grubby fingerprints had been left all over it from piles of discarded rubbish and food to wear and tear on the monuments and pathway.<br>It is still worth a visit but be prepared to see history clash with modernity.</span></div></div><div class="lszDU" style="line-height: 22px;"><button class="UikNM _G B- _S _T c G_ P0 wSSLS wnNQG" type="button"><span class="biGQs _P XWJSj Wb">Read more</span><div class="CECjK"><svg viewBox="0 0 25 24" width="20px" height="20px" class="d Vb UmNoP"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M5.188 7.521l6.836 6.837 6.837-6.837 1.06 1.06-7.366 7.368a.75.75 0 01-1.061 0L4.127 8.582l1.06-1.06z"></path></svg></div></button></div></div><div></div><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB xUqsL mowmC KxBGd"><a target="_blank" tabindex="0" href="/Attraction_Review-g304555-d2443557-Reviews-Galtaji_Temple-Jaipur_Jaipur_District_Rajasthan.html#REVIEWS" class="BMQDV _F G- wSSLS SwZTJ FGwzt suezE">Review of: Galtaji Temple</a></div><div class="TreSq"><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB ncFvv osNWb">Written 23 November 2022</div><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB mowmC osNWb">This review is the subjective opinion of a Tripadvisor member and not of Tripadvisor LLC. class="yCeTE">Central Park Jaipur is a huge open space right in the heart of the city. There is a huge polo ground and Golf course attached to it. The entire round of the park is about4-5 km and there are a lot of people who come here for a jog or a brisk walk. There are a few birds around and a lot of greenery.<br><br>The central park also has a 206 feet high first day and night monumental National flag 28 feet wide and 72 feet in length. class="BMQDV _F G- wSSLS SwZTJ FGwzt ukgoS"><span class="yCeTE">World's Largest Cannon of Ancient Era </span></a></div><div class="_T FKffI bmUTE"><div class="fIrGe _T bgMZj" has its Abode at the Jaigarh Fort of Jaipur. <br><br>The cannon has a barrel of 20.2 ft and weighs 50 tonne.  <br>The cannon tears on a  a two-wheeled vehicle and the wheels are about 5ft in diameter. Apart from this, the vehicle also has two removable additional wheels for transport, their diameter is about 9 feet.<br><br>The cannon has the capacity of being fed with 100 kg of gunpowder with 50 kg shell making it able to fire package load of 150kgs.<br><br>The cannon was fired only once, with 100 kilograms of gunpowder, and when fired was claimed to have covered a distance of about 35 kilometres. It is said that the projectile fired from it made a small lake in Chaksu.<br><br>As per the stories doing the rounds and being believed, the impact was so powerful that it actually lived to its words as Weapon of  Mass destruction. The loud noise created by the blow made people deaf and pregnant women suffered miscarriages. Seeing this destruction of large scale it was never used again.  <br><br>But being a lethal weapon with immense power it was kept in the fort as a backbone. And the Royal family still gets it maintained every year and prays before it once a year by performing the Swastik Pooja. <br><br>Must visit place as you explore Jaipur. <br><br>Stay connected as I bring more stories from the Pink city of Forts - Jaipur. <br><br>Fort timings : 9am to 5pm <br>ticket price : Rs. 100 for Indians  Rs. 200 for foreigners</span></div></div><div class="lszDU" style="line-height: 22px;"><button class="UikNM _G B- _S _T c G_ P0 wSSLS wnNQG" type="button"><span class="biGQs _P XWJSj Wb">Read more</span><div class="CECjK"><svg viewBox="0 0 25 24" width="20px" height="20px" class="d Vb UmNoP"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M5.188 7.521l6.836 6.837 6.837-6.837 1.06 1.06-7.366 7.368a.75.75 0 01-1.061 0L4.127 8.582l1.06-1.06z"></path></svg></div></button></div></div><div></div><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB xUqsL mowmC KxBGd"><a target="_blank" tabindex="0" href="/Attraction_Review-g304555-d8548736-Reviews-Jaivana-Jaipur_Jaipur_District_Rajasthan.html#REVIEWS" class="BMQDV _F G- wSSLS SwZTJ FGwzt suezE">Review of: Jaivana</a></div><div class="TreSq"><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB ncFvv osNWb">Written 4 January 2023</div><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB mowmC osNWb">This review is the subjective opinion of a Tripadvisor member and not of Tripadvisor LLC. 0)"></path></svg></div><div class="biGQs _P fiohW qWPrE ncFvv fOtGX"><a target="_blank" tabindex="0" href="/ShowUserReviews-g304555-d4810388-r874812015-Jagat_Shiromani_Ji_Temple-Jaipur_Jaipur_District_Rajasthan.html" class="BMQDV _F G- wSSLS SwZTJ FGwzt ukgoS"><span class="yCeTE">The temple of Meera Bai </span></a></div><div class="_T FKffI bmUTE"><div class="fIrGe _T bgMZj" style="-webkit-line-clamp: 7; line-break: normal; cursor: pointer;"><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB KxBGd"><span class="yCeTE">Built in 1600 AD by the king Sawai Maan Singh in the memory of his son Jagat Singh, this temple located in Amer, Rajastan is dedicated to Lord Krishna and the devotee Meera Bai. <br><br>The temple contains a statue of Lord Shri Krishna which is believed to be the same statue that Meera Bai worshipped in the State of Mewar. This idol was saved from being destroyed during the Mughal attack on Mewar by Amer rulers &amp; was brought to Amer. And for that very reason it is also known as Meera Bai temple. <br><br>The striking architectural elements of the temple are a blend of different architectural styles taking inspiration from Mughal, Jain, and Hindu, Mughal ones. At the entrance of the temple, you will come across a beautiful marble archway which is being guarded by two marble elephants. Surprisingly, the archway and the elephants have been carved from a single piece of stone. <br><br>The temple is connected to the Amer Palace having two entrances, where the first one leads you to the Palace and other one leads you to the Amer town. This temple was built beside the courtyard of the Amer palace in a way so that the queen could easily visit the temple anytime. <br><br>Whenever you plan to visit Jaipur, explore the streets of Amer with a visit to this divine place. <br><br>Timings:  06:00 AM to 01:00 PM;  04:00 PM to 08:00 PM</span></div></div><div class="lszDU" style="line-height: 22px;"><button class="UikNM _G B- _S _T c G_ P0 wSSLS wnNQG" type="button"><span class="biGQs _P XWJSj Wb">Read more</span><div class="CECjK"><svg viewBox="0 0 25 24" width="20px" height="20px" class="d Vb UmNoP"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M5.188 7.521l6.836 6.837 6.837-6.837 1.06 1.06-7.366 7.368a.75.75 0 01-1.061 0L4.127 8.582l1.06-1.06z"></path></svg></div></button></div></div><div></div><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB xUqsL mowmC KxBGd"><a target="_blank" tabindex="0" href="/Attraction_Review-g304555-d4810388-Reviews-Jagat_Shiromani_Ji_Temple-Jaipur_Jaipur_District_Rajasthan.html#REVIEWS" class="BMQDV _F G- wSSLS SwZTJ FGwzt suezE">Review of: Jagat Shiromani Ji Temple</a></div><div class="TreSq"><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB ncFvv osNWb">Written 11 January 2023</div><div class="biGQs _P pZUbB mowmC osNWb">This review is the subjective opinion of a Tripadvisor member and not of Tripadvisor LLC.
